						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Espozo wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm assuming [moving the video scaler from inside the monitor to inside the GPU] never actually took place, because I've used TVs with such underpowered processors that it feels like there is a third of a second of input lag. What kind of hardware does the average 1080p TV have, or would it vary to much to accurately guess? Is it just some off the shelf ARM processor?<br /></div>What? It's in every laptop. Probably most cell phones. As a result, it's in your desktop GPU also, because laptops are where the volume market is.<br /><br />Whatever flat panel LCD monitor you have <em>probably</em> has its own scaler <em>also</em>.<br /><br />While it's possible that the device inside your television might use an older style in-order framebuffer, honestly the lag is there <em>because they have no reason to avoid it</em>. It's simply not something that's important to the mass market. And it does let them do some limited acausal image processing, which they think looks/sells better.</div>

