						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Espozo wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">adam_smasher wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">OISC</div><br />Wtf? <img src="./images/smilies/icon_lol.gif" alt=":lol:" title="Laughing" /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Modern framebuffers often aren't linear in-order chunks of memory anymore.</div><br />How are they then? I thought a framebuffer was just a giant area of memory with each row of pixels onscreen being at a different offset in the framebuffer.</div><br />This is true and not true. <br /><br />PowerVR based GPUs use &quot;tiled&quot; rendering, this means the GPU makes buckets and once a bucket has enough changes it will then process that &quot;tile&quot; and update the screen. This allows it to save on power, which is nice for batteries and for Thermals. So anything that is basically a mobile phone has this type of GPU, the Pi is basically a like a mobile phone. the Dreamcast has a PowerVR GPU and the PS2 has a similar architecture and its like lots and lots of little triangles. <br /> <br />On a windows PC with a Geforce anything... its has the bandwidth, thermal and power that you can just throw a 1080p linear frame buffer down the bus each frame and be done with it.</div>

